ef="./Talmud#cite_ref-20" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-20" class="mw-reference-text">e.g. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pirkei_Avot" title="Pirkei Avot" id="mwA-s">Pirkei Avot</a> 5.21: "five for the Torah, ten for Mishnah, thirteen for the commandments, fifteen for <i id="mwA-w">talmud</i>".</span></li><li about="#cite_note-21" id="cite_note-21"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-21" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-21" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt74" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/loc/Talmud.html"},"title":{"wt":"Judaic Treasures of the Library of Congress: The Talmud"},"publisher":{"wt":"American-Israeli Cooperative Enterprise"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA-0"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/loc/Talmud.html" id="mwA-4">"Judaic Treasures of the Library of Congress: The Talmud"</a>. American-Israeli Cooperative Enterprise.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Judaic+Treasures+of+the+Library+of+Congress%3A+The+Talmud&amp;rft.pub=American-Israeli+Cooperative+Enterprise&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jewishvirtuallibrary.org%2Fjsource%2Floc%2FTalmud.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATalmud" class="Z3988" about="#mwt74" id="mwA-8"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt74" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwA_A"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-22" id="cite_note-22"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-22" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-22" class="mw-reference-text">Sáenz-Badillos, Ángel and John Elwolde. 1996. A history of the Hebrew language. pp. 170–171: "There is general agreement that two main periods of RH (Rabbinical Hebrew) can be distinguished. The first, which lasted until the close of the Tannaitic era (around 200 CE), is characterized by RH as a spoken language gradually developing into a literary medium in which the Mishnah, Tosefta, <i id="mwA_E">baraitot</i>, and Tannaitic <i id="mwA_I">midrashim</i> would be composed. The second stage begins with the <i id="mwA_M">Amoraim</i>, and sees RH being replaced by Aramaic as the spoken vernacular, surviving only as a literary language. Then it continued to be used in later rabbinic writings until the 10th century in, for example, the Hebrew portions of the two Talmuds and in midrashic and haggadic literature."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-23" id="cite_note-23"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-23" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-23" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt83" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/3490-bomberg-daniel"},"title":{"wt":"Bomberg, Daniel"},"website":{"wt":"www.jewishencyclopedia.com"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA_Q"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/3490-bomberg-daniel" id="mwA_U">"Bomberg, Daniel"</a>. <i id="mwA_Y">www.jewishencyclopedia.com</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=www.jewishencyclopedia.com&amp;rft.atitle=Bomberg%2C+Daniel&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.jewishencyclopedia.com%2Farticles%2F3490-bomberg-daniel&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3