.org/talmud-yerushalmi-mevoar/</span></li><li about="#cite_note-47" id="cite_note-47"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-47" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-47" class="mw-reference-text">As Pirkei Avot is a tractate of the Mishnah, and reached its final form centuries before the compilation of either Talmud, this refers to <i id="mwBEc"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Talmud#Gemara" id="mwBEg">talmud</a></i> as an activity rather than to any written compilation.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-48" id="cite_note-48"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-48" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-48" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt147" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://hebrewbooks.org/40633"},"title":{"wt":"HebrewBooks.org Sefer Detail: ספר הנר – ברכות  –  אגמתי, זכריה בן יהודה"},"publisher":{"wt":""}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBEk"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://hebrewbooks.org/40633" id="mwBEo">"HebrewBooks.org Sefer Detail: ספר הנר – ברכות  –  אגמתי, זכריה בן יהודה"</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=HebrewBooks.org+Sefer+Detail%3A+%D7%A1%D7%A4%D7%A8+%D7%94%D7%A0%D7%A8+%E2%80%93+%D7%91%D7%A8%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%AA++%E2%80%93++%D7%90%D7%92%D7%9E%D7%AA%D7%99%2C+%D7%96%D7%9B%D7%A8%D7%99%D7%94+%D7%91%D7%9F+%D7%99%D7%94%D7%95%D7%93%D7%94&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fhebrewbooks.org%2F40633&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATalmud" class="Z3988" about="#mwt147" id="mwBEs"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt147" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBEw"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-49" id="cite_note-49"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-49" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-49" class="mw-reference-text">For a list see Ephraim Urbach, s.v. "Tosafot," in <i id="mwBE0">Encyclopedia of Religion</i>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-50" id="cite_note-50"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-50" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-50" class="mw-reference-text">See <i id="mwBE4">Pilpul</i>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mordechai_Breuer" title="Mordechai Breuer" id="mwBE8">Mordechai Breuer</a>, in <i id="mwBFA">Encyclopaedia Judaica</i>, Vol. 16, 2nd Ed (2007), Macmillan Reference and H.H. Ben Sasson, <i id="mwBFE">A History of the Jewish People</i>, pp. 627, 717.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-51" id="cite_note-51"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-51" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-51" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwBFI">Kol Melechet Higgayon</i>, the Hebrew translation of Averroes' epitome of Aristotle's logical works, was widely studied in northern Italy, particularly <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Padua" title="Padua" id="mwBFM">Padua</a>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-52" id="cite_note-52"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-52" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-52" class="mw-reference-text">Boyarin, <i id="mwBFQ">Sephardi Speculation</i> (Hebrew) (Jerusalem 1989).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-53" id="cite_note-53"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-53" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-53" class="mw-reference-text">For a comprehensive treatment, see Ravitzky, below.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-54" id="cite_note-54"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-54" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-54" class="mw-reference-text">Faur is here describing the tradition of Damascus, though the approach in other places may have been similar.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-55" id="cite_note-55"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-55" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-55" class="mw-reference-text">Examples of lessons using this approach may be found <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.moreshetsepharad.org/GEMARA.html" id="mwBFU">here</a><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:All_articles_with_dead_external_links" about="#mwt178" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"dead link","href":"./Template:Dead_link"},"params":{"date":{"wt":"December 2017"},"bot":{"wt":"InternetArchiveBot"},"fix-attempted":{"wt":"yes"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBFY"/><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_dead_external_links_from_December_2017" about="#mwt178" id="mwBFc"/><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" about="#mwt178" id="mwBFg"><span style="white-space: nowrap;" id="mwBFk"><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBFo">[</span><i id="mwBFs"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wikipedia:Link_rot" title="Wikipedia:Link rot" id="mwBFw"><span title=" Dead link since December 2017" id="mwBF0">permanent dead link</span></a></i><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBF4">]</span></span></sup><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_permanently_dead_external_links" about="#mwt178" id="mwBF8"/>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-56" id="cite_note-56"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-56" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-56" class="mw-reference-text">Cf. the distinction in the Ashkenazi yeshivah curriculum between <i id="mwBGA">beki'ut</i> (basic familiarization) and<i id="mwBGE"> 'iyyun</i> (in-depth study).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-57" id="cite_note-57"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-57" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-57" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./David_ben_Judah_Messer_Leon" title="David ben Judah Messer Leon" id="mwBGI">David ben Judah Messer Leon</a>, <i id="mwBGM">Kevod Ḥakhamim</i>, cited by Zimmels, <i id="mwBGQ">Ashkenazim and Sephardim</i>, pp. 151, 154.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-58" id="cite_note-58"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-58" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-58" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chaim_Joseph_David_Azulai" title="Chaim Joseph David Azulai" id="mwBGU" class="mw-redirect">Chaim Joseph David Azulai</a>, <i id="mwBGY">Shem Gedolim</i>, cited Hirschberg, <i id="mwBGc">A History of the Jews in North Africa</i>, pp. 125–126.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-59" id="cite_note-59"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-59" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-59" class="mw-reference-text">Joseph Ringel, "A Third Way: <i id="mwBGg">Iyyun Tunisai</i> as a Traditional Critical Method of Talmud Study", <i id="mwBGk">Tradition</i> 2013 46:3.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-60" id="cite_note-60"><a href="./Talmud#cite_ref-60" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-60" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt186" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web ","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://www.halachabrura.org/"},"title":{"wt":"A labor of great magnitude stands before us, to repair the break between the Talmudic deliberations and the halachic decisions... to accustom students of the Gemara to correlate knowledge of all the halacha with its 